WORLD OF TEQUILA ED APP TEQUILA DEFINITION MODULE
EDUCATION
1. Tequila is a product of Mexico and can be made only in the state of Jalisco and small
denominated portions of 4 surrounding states - Tamaulipas, Nayarit, Michoacán, and
Guanajuato.
2. Tequila received a Designation of Origin (appellation de controlee) in 1974. It’s the same as an
appellation for Bordeaux, Bourbon or Cognac. The Mexican federal government has
established strict requirements governing tequila production.
3. Tequila can only be made from the Blue Agave, grown in specified regions of Jalisco, while
mezcal can be made from many different varieties of agave such as Espadin, Cenizo and
Tobala.
4. Tequila never has a worm in its bottle. The worm is found only in certain bottles of mezcal.
5. Normas are production standards set by the Mexican Government. Normas specify what
tequila is and how it must be made. Each bottle of real tequila must have a NOM (Normas
Oficiales Mexicanas) 4-digit number on the bottle. This number indicates the distillery where
the Tequila is made.
